---
import GuidedSolution from '../../components/learning/GuidedSolution';
import SourceLinks from '../../components/SourceLinks.astro';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const seminarFiles = [
  'Problem sets/Seminar 1/GRA6631_TA1_Exercises.pdf',
  'Problem sets/Seminar 1/GRA6631_NaturalRate.pdf',
  'Problem sets/Seminar 1/Seminar_1_GRA6631_2025_Solutions.pdf',
];
---

<BaseLayout title="Seminar 1 Workbench | Economic Policy Study Site">
  <section class="article-grid">
    <article class="article-shell">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Problem-solving support</p>
        <h1>Seminar 1 Workbench</h1>
        <p class="card-subtitle">Baseline New Keynesian model shock reasoning</p>
      </div>

      <p>
        This workbench uses the Seminar 1 sheet equations directly. The first guided exercise focuses on the
        qualitative impact of a temporary positive technology shock in the baseline NK model.
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        Scope note: this solution path is tied to the model structure used in course material. If your lecture
        notation differs slightly, map each step conceptually rather than memorizing symbols.
      </div>

      <GuidedSolution
        client:load
        id="exercise:seminar1:technology-shock"
        title="Exercise 1: Temporary positive technology shock"
        prompt="Suppose the economy starts in steady state and is hit by a temporary positive technology shock. Describe the impact response of output, potential output, inflation, and the natural real interest rate."
        hints={[
          'Start by separating actual output from potential output. Both can move in the same direction while the output gap behaves differently.',
          'Use the marginal-cost channel: higher productivity reduces unit labor cost pressure for given wages.',
          'For the natural real rate, use the course expression and check the sign on the technology-shock term.',
        ]}
        steps={[
          {
            title: 'Step 1: Map the shock into production conditions',
            detail:
              'A positive technology shock raises productivity. In the NK setup, this pushes flexible-price (potential) output up on impact.',
          },
          {
            title: 'Step 2: Determine potential output',
            detail:
              'Potential output rises because the economy can produce more with given inputs when productivity is higher. This is the direct supply-side effect.',
          },
          {
            title: 'Step 3: Reason about inflation via marginal cost',
            detail:
              'The seminar equations link inflation to marginal-cost pressure. A positive productivity shock tends to reduce real marginal cost pressure, which pushes inflation downward on impact in the baseline case.',
          },
          {
            title: 'Step 4: Reason about actual output',
            detail:
              'Actual output typically rises on impact, but the size depends on policy response and demand-side terms. The robust direction in this setup is an increase in activity relative to the pre-shock steady state.',
          },
          {
            title: 'Step 5: Use the natural-rate expression for sign discipline',
            detail:
              'In the course model family, the natural real rate includes a technology-shock term with negative loading when persistence is below one. Under that parameterization, a temporary positive technology shock lowers the natural real rate on impact.',
          },
          {
            title: 'Step 6: Final qualitative summary',
            detail:
              'Impact directions (baseline): output up, potential output up, inflation down, natural real rate down. Always mention that magnitudes and exact paths depend on persistence and policy closure.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </article>

    <div>
      <SourceLinks files={seminarFiles} title="Seminar 1 Sources" />
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
